SIMPLE: surge
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Surge
<hw>Surge</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>surgere</ets>,
<ets>surrectum</ets>, to raise, to rise; <ets>sub</ets> under +
<ets>regere</ets> to direct: cf. OF. <ets>surgeon</ets>,
<ets>sourgeon</ets>, fountain. See <er>Regent</er>, and cf.
<er>Insurrection</er>, <er>Sortie</er>, <er>Source</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A spring; a fountain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Divers <xex>surges</xex> and springs of water.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ld.
Berners.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A large wave or billow; a great, rolling swell of
water, produced generally by a high wind.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that doubteth is like the <qex>surge</qex> of the sea driven by
the wind and tossed.</q> <rj><qau>James i. 6 (Rev. Ver.)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He flies aloft, and, with impetuous roar,⟦br⟧
Pursues the foaming <qex>surges</qex> to the shore.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The motion of, or produced by, a great
wave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The tapered part of a windlass barrel or a capstan,
upon which the cable surges, or slips.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Surge
<hw>Surge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To swell; to rise hifg
and roll.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>surging</qex> waters like a mountain rise.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To slip along a
windlass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Surge
<hw>Surge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Surged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Surging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>surgir</ets> to cast anchor, to land. Cf. <er>Surge</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To let go or slacken
suddenly, as a rope; <as>as, to <ex>surge</ex> a hawser or
messenger</as>; also, to slacken the rope about (a capstan).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surgeful</ent>⟦br⟧
